00:25:52.170 --> 00:25:54.810
you should be with each other.

00:25:54.810 --> 00:25:57.400
In other words, let's say you
and I have a disagreement.

00:25:57.400 --> 00:26:01.600
OK, rather than being caught in
the anger of that disagreement,

00:26:01.600 --> 00:26:05.070
to go above and you should
say, how do we disagree?

00:26:05.070 --> 00:26:06.540
How should we disagree?

00:26:06.540 --> 00:26:10.280
Form a contract of how you
should be with each other,

00:26:10.280 --> 00:26:13.532
and make that a
practical modus operandi.

00:26:13.532 --> 00:26:14.990
That's what we do,
and then there's

00:26:14.990 --> 00:26:16.850
also then the ways we do it.

00:26:16.850 --> 00:26:19.920
So the ways we do it
are certain things.

00:26:19.920 --> 00:26:27.670
First, to know that
decision-making

00:26:27.670 --> 00:26:30.450
is a 2-step process.

00:26:30.450 --> 00:26:35.780
There is first taking in,
and then there's deciding.

00:26:35.780 --> 00:26:40.270
The capacity to take in the
other person's point of view,

00:26:40.270 --> 00:26:44.770
the noticing how your
body is reacting,

00:26:44.770 --> 00:26:46.570
noticing how you are reacting.

00:26:46.570 --> 00:26:49.030
Am I having my heart rate rise?

00:26:49.030 --> 00:26:51.260
Can I pause?

00:26:51.260 --> 00:26:53.910
We have something like
the two-minute rule.

00:26:53.910 --> 00:26:58.230
You say, can I have two minutes?

00:26:58.230 --> 00:27:01.170
Then that person has the two
minutes to say what they want.

00:27:04.230 --> 00:27:05.900
Having those kinds
of protocols--

00:27:05.900 --> 00:27:09.920
there are a number
explained in the book.

00:27:09.920 --> 00:27:14.460
Where there's curiosity,
where there's not blocking.

00:27:14.460 --> 00:27:18.580
Somebody in a
discussion will do a lot

00:27:18.580 --> 00:27:21.010
to block the taking it in.

00:27:21.010 --> 00:27:22.890
So these protocols--

00:27:22.890 --> 00:27:24.410
I won't go through them all.

00:27:24.410 --> 00:27:28.270
But having those protocols
in place that you practice

00:27:28.270 --> 00:27:29.870
are fair.

00:27:29.870 --> 00:27:35.610
I have created an app called
a Dispute Resolver, OK?

00:27:35.610 --> 00:27:39.240
So when anybody has a
dispute, you push the button,

00:27:39.240 --> 00:27:41.820
and there's a path, and
the dispute's resolved.

00:27:41.820 --> 00:27:44.400
It's explained in the
appendix of the book.

00:27:44.400 --> 00:27:46.440
All the tools are there.

00:27:46.440 --> 00:27:49.470
And it describes
procedurally what one does,

00:27:49.470 --> 00:27:51.960
depending on the
level of the dispute.

00:27:51.960 --> 00:27:55.650
A very common thing is if
you and I have a dispute,

00:27:55.650 --> 00:27:57.960
one of the simplest
things to do is for you

00:27:57.960 --> 00:28:00.695
and I mutually
agree on a mediator.

00:28:04.069 --> 00:28:05.860
So we agree on a mediator
and move forward.

00:28:05.860 --> 00:28:08.570
Some others might be
matters of principle

00:28:08.570 --> 00:28:11.775
and almost progress
like legal cases.

00:28:11.775 --> 00:28:12.650
What's your evidence?

00:28:12.650 --> 00:28:13.150
What's this?

00:28:13.150 --> 00:28:15.357
And who is the judge?

00:28:15.357 --> 00:28:17.440
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Now,
when you have this dialogue

00:28:17.440 --> 00:28:19.630
and discussion about
feedback, and it

00:28:19.630 --> 00:28:21.940
might turn into
a tense situation

00:28:21.940 --> 00:28:24.780
like with disagreement, are
there mediums of exchange

00:28:24.780 --> 00:28:25.856
that you prioritize?

00:28:25.856 --> 00:28:29.330
Because I see some people
who will go towards email,

00:28:29.330 --> 00:28:33.700
but when you use email, you miss
tone and content and context.

00:28:33.700 --> 00:28:35.380
RAY DALIO: As a
generalization, we

00:28:35.380 --> 00:28:38.680
want the person to find
the medium of exchange

00:28:38.680 --> 00:28:41.380
that they're most comfortable
with because there

00:28:41.380 --> 00:28:43.540
are pros and cons to each.

00:28:43.540 --> 00:28:45.970
Like, some people,
in the moment,

00:28:45.970 --> 00:28:49.090
feel that they're not as
spontaneous in the moment,

00:28:49.090 --> 00:28:51.130
or they may be more introverted.

00:28:51.130 --> 00:28:54.240
And they think that they won't
present themselves the best

00:28:54.240 --> 00:28:56.950
in a person,
one-on-one discussion

00:28:56.950 --> 00:28:59.920
so that they would prefer
by email to say, listen,

00:28:59.920 --> 00:29:04.270
I'd like to lay out my thoughts,
hear your thoughts by email,

00:29:04.270 --> 00:29:07.180
and then have that opportunity
to have the back-and-forth.

00:29:07.180 --> 00:29:09.179
Some people would like
to do it other ways.

00:29:09.179 --> 00:29:10.720
The important thing
is that they just

00:29:10.720 --> 00:29:12.884
agree on what's most
effective for them.

00:29:12.884 --> 00:29:14.050
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Excellent.

00:29:14.050 --> 00:29:18.280
Now, let's say an organization
goes through a calamity

00:29:18.280 --> 00:29:22.120
and there's a trust issue
in the organization,

00:29:22.120 --> 00:29:25.980
how does the company
go about rebuilding

00:29:25.980 --> 00:29:28.720
the trust within employees?

00:29:28.720 --> 00:29:31.900
RAY DALIO: Well, again, I
think radical truthfulness

00:29:31.900 --> 00:29:35.550
and radical transparency
is the means of doing it.

00:29:35.550 --> 00:29:40.410
What I did and what my
experience would be--

00:29:40.410 --> 00:29:44.360
if you have radical
transparency--

00:29:44.360 --> 00:29:50.360
so literally, every crisis I was
in, every situation I was in,

00:29:50.360 --> 00:29:54.200
I would have a camera
in that discussion

00:29:54.200 --> 00:29:57.410
as we looked at the pros
and cons of the issue

00:29:57.410 --> 00:30:01.130
so everybody could see the pros
and cons of that discussion

00:30:01.130 --> 00:30:03.560
so you know there's no spin.

00:30:03.560 --> 00:30:07.580
You have a trust issue if
it's hidden behind the scenes,

00:30:07.580 --> 00:30:08.480
I think.

00:30:08.480 --> 00:30:11.450
With radical transparency,
so everybody could see.

00:30:11.450 --> 00:30:17.000
Just imagine what it would be
like here, OK, for whatever

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:21.290
issue, that you could see
how people making decisions,

00:30:21.290 --> 00:30:23.450
literally, weighing
the pros and cons

00:30:23.450 --> 00:30:25.550
and seeing how they are real.

00:30:25.550 --> 00:30:28.010
And it could be anything from
the top of the organization

00:30:28.010 --> 00:30:31.430
to just even somebody
firing somebody else.

00:30:31.430 --> 00:30:32.870
Was it done well?

00:30:32.870 --> 00:30:36.620
That radical transparency
and then coming out of it

00:30:36.620 --> 00:30:41.150
and writing principles as to,
why did you handle it that way,

00:30:41.150 --> 00:30:43.460
and then putting
those principles out

00:30:43.460 --> 00:30:45.770
so that everybody could
debate that principle

00:30:45.770 --> 00:30:48.800
or look at that principle, not
in an enormous, time-consuming

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:52.070
way but in an effective
way and then having an idea

00:30:52.070 --> 00:30:54.440
meritocratic way
where you look at that

00:30:54.440 --> 00:30:57.050
and you say, OK, that
decision was made that way.

00:30:57.050 --> 00:30:58.970
Maybe that's not the
way I would do it.

00:30:58.970 --> 00:31:02.370
But I now understand
the thinking behind it.

00:31:02.370 --> 00:31:06.080
Because if you don't
have that kind of thing,

00:31:06.080 --> 00:31:08.510
then there's alienation.

00:31:08.510 --> 00:31:12.410
If you don't have trust and
you don't have an appreciation,

00:31:12.410 --> 00:31:14.960
then increasingly, you build
an organization in which

00:31:14.960 --> 00:31:16.930
there's a "we" and "them."

00:31:16.930 --> 00:31:19.970
There's those people who
are making the decisions,

00:31:19.970 --> 00:31:22.980
and you don't really
understand it.

00:31:22.980 --> 00:31:25.670
And you just have
to go along with it.

00:31:25.670 --> 00:31:30.560
And then that becomes
a source of tension.

00:31:30.560 --> 00:31:33.110
And then there are
factions and all that.

00:31:33.110 --> 00:31:34.910
And there's no resolution.

00:31:34.910 --> 00:31:38.330
You have to have
resolution and get past it.

00:31:38.330 --> 00:31:43.400
So the radical truthfulness
and the radical transparency

00:31:43.400 --> 00:31:44.330
brings trust.

00:31:44.330 --> 00:31:46.830
And it means that bad stuff--

00:31:46.830 --> 00:31:49.880
it's tough stuff bad stuff
to happen because bad stuff

00:31:49.880 --> 00:31:51.501
happens in the dark.

00:31:51.501 --> 00:31:52.750
JORDAN THIBODEAU: That's true.

00:31:52.750 --> 00:31:55.800
RAY DALIO: If you make
it radically transparent

00:31:55.800 --> 00:31:58.320
and anybody can bring it
up, then everybody owns it.

00:31:58.320 --> 00:32:02.130
Radical transparency is
a very effective tool

00:32:02.130 --> 00:32:04.890
in terms of building trust and
putting things to the light.

00:32:04.890 --> 00:32:06.810
Believe me, none
of this is perfect,

00:32:06.810 --> 00:32:10.020
but it's certainly
been miraculous for us.

00:32:10.660 --> 00:32:12.870
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Excellent.

00:32:12.870 --> 00:32:15.030
Why do you think
organizations aren't going

00:32:15.030 --> 00:32:16.520
towards radical transparency?

00:32:19.300 --> 00:32:23.830
RAY DALIO: First of all, I
think that they inevitably will.

00:32:23.830 --> 00:32:29.112
You must know that it's so easy
to collect data on everybody.

00:32:29.112 --> 00:32:32.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:32.920 --> 00:32:35.440
So everybody's going to
know what everybody's like,

00:32:35.440 --> 00:32:38.260
and then the question is, who's
got the radical transparency?

00:32:41.456 --> 00:32:42.830
And then what are
you going to do

00:32:42.830 --> 00:32:45.380
with the radical transparency?

00:32:45.380 --> 00:32:49.060
You're going to make what you do
with it radically transparent?

00:32:49.060 --> 00:32:52.960
OK, so I think
evolutionarily, we're

00:32:52.960 --> 00:32:56.880
going to go to this
radical truthfulness

00:32:56.880 --> 00:32:58.630
and this radical
transparency because it's

00:32:58.630 --> 00:33:01.120
going to be tough to hide.

00:33:01.120 --> 00:33:07.730
I think it's a control
thing and time thing.

00:33:07.730 --> 00:33:11.090
So it's a control thing means
you're a decision maker,

00:33:11.090 --> 00:33:14.420
and all these people have all
these different points of view.

00:33:14.420 --> 00:33:17.010
And how meritocratic
is it to hear all this?

00:33:17.010 --> 00:33:18.669
And we'll never
resolve those things.

00:33:18.669 --> 00:33:20.210
Somebody just wants
to sort of get on

00:33:20.210 --> 00:33:21.690
with their decision-making.

00:33:21.690 --> 00:33:23.630
And I think that that's
because they're still

00:33:23.630 --> 00:33:30.150
in this, what I believe,
will be an old world mindset,

00:33:30.150 --> 00:33:35.130
that it is all in the head,
rather than out of the head

00:33:35.130 --> 00:33:37.650
and in that notion of
how do you make the best

00:33:37.650 --> 00:33:40.740
algorithmic decision-making
so it's not in the head.

00:33:40.740 --> 00:33:42.780
But we still have
the, it's in my head,

00:33:42.780 --> 00:33:45.950
and I want to do what I want
to do, and I know better.

00:33:45.950 --> 00:33:47.185
And how do I do that?

00:33:47.185 --> 00:33:48.060
That's a big part of.

00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:48.559
It

00:33:48.559 --> 00:33:50.730
And then thinking, of
course, about the time

00:33:50.730 --> 00:33:53.280
of, how do you resolve
it with all these people

00:33:53.280 --> 00:33:56.310
so that you have a real
time-efficient, effective way

00:33:56.310 --> 00:33:58.260
of having an idea meritocracy.

00:33:58.260 --> 00:34:00.000
Those are the barriers.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:02.640
And then there's this
two you thing, OK?

00:34:02.640 --> 00:34:04.930
That emotional you thing.

00:34:04.930 --> 00:34:07.385
Those are the, I would
say, the main barriers.

00:34:07.385 --> 00:34:08.340
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Now,
you said what's important

00:34:08.340 --> 00:34:10.006
for the mission of
Bridgewater is having

00:34:10.006 --> 00:34:12.690
meaningful relationships.

00:34:12.690 --> 00:34:15.210
Have you found that
with this transparency

00:34:15.210 --> 00:34:18.679
you've been able to
supercharge the relationships

00:34:18.679 --> 00:34:22.020
that you've had in the company?

00:34:22.020 --> 00:34:25.989
RAY DALIO: Yeah, yes.

00:34:25.989 --> 00:34:28.880
But we don't even have to
go to the company level.

00:34:28.880 --> 00:34:31.389
I'm just saying any
group of individuals

00:34:31.389 --> 00:34:33.610
can decide whether
they're going to be

00:34:33.610 --> 00:34:35.679
radically truthful
and transparent

00:34:35.679 --> 00:34:37.989
and on the same mission.

00:34:37.989 --> 00:34:40.000
If you get five people
together and they

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:41.800
say we're going to be on that--

00:34:41.800 --> 00:34:43.449
And that's largely
where it started to

00:34:43.449 --> 00:34:45.790
because I start the
company, and I say, how am I

00:34:45.790 --> 00:34:48.820
going to be with each other?

00:34:48.820 --> 00:34:52.690
Because that honesty and
being on that mission

00:34:52.690 --> 00:34:54.598
is going to bring
people closer together.

00:34:54.598 --> 00:34:56.389
It almost brings
everybody closer together.

00:34:56.389 --> 00:35:00.400
The hiding stuff and the
absence of trust is bad.

00:35:00.400 --> 00:35:02.410
And not only the
absence of trust,

00:35:02.410 --> 00:35:06.700
but you can't have
real ownership if you

00:35:06.700 --> 00:35:10.660
don't understand and
don't have a say.

00:35:10.660 --> 00:35:12.460
Everybody-- and like
I'm saying-- everybody

00:35:12.460 --> 00:35:17.770
has the right and obligation
to make sense of things.

00:35:17.770 --> 00:35:19.300
It's powerful.

00:35:19.300 --> 00:35:21.160
And when you were
in it together,

00:35:21.160 --> 00:35:23.760
something much more
magical happens

00:35:23.760 --> 00:35:25.300
than a paycheck and a job.

00:35:27.342 --> 00:35:29.800
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Now, when
you've created your principles,

00:35:29.800 --> 00:35:32.060
has there been processes
where you said,

00:35:32.060 --> 00:35:34.240
maybe this principle
worked at this point,

00:35:34.240 --> 00:35:35.890
but now we need
to re-evaluate it?

00:35:35.890 --> 00:35:37.540
RAY DALIO: Constantly.

00:35:37.540 --> 00:35:42.430
Because so I guess I
want to to describe it.

00:35:42.430 --> 00:35:47.740
I just about everything
happens over and over again.

00:35:50.680 --> 00:35:53.860
We instead look at things
as individual things

00:35:53.860 --> 00:35:56.800
that are coming up so it's
like we're in a snowstorm.

00:35:56.800 --> 00:36:01.150
But if you just sort of
say, what species of thing,

00:36:01.150 --> 00:36:04.300
what species of
encounter am I having?

00:36:04.300 --> 00:36:05.880
And you write a
principle for it,

00:36:05.880 --> 00:36:10.780
and you write that, then when
the next one comes along again,

00:36:10.780 --> 00:36:13.750
you see, ah, it's that species.

00:36:13.750 --> 00:36:16.030
And you go to that principle,
and you look at it,

00:36:16.030 --> 00:36:18.680
and everyone's
slightly different.

00:36:18.680 --> 00:36:21.640
And that leads to then the
refinement of the principles

00:36:21.640 --> 00:36:23.650
and those differences, right?

00:36:23.650 --> 00:36:26.620
And then to do that
transparently is very powerful.

00:36:26.620 --> 00:36:29.950
So yeah, always.

00:36:29.950 --> 00:36:35.410
And you realize, of course,
that no principle is perfect.

00:36:35.410 --> 00:36:36.560
No principle works.

00:36:36.560 --> 00:36:39.850
So those different gradations
get more fleshed out

00:36:39.850 --> 00:36:41.440
and become clear.

00:36:41.440 --> 00:36:44.810
And that's what the book
of "Principles" is about.

00:36:44.810 --> 00:36:46.240
It's a bunch of these things.

00:36:46.240 --> 00:36:48.399
But you'll see how
they've sort of evolved

00:36:48.399 --> 00:36:49.940
from this encounter
or that encounter

00:36:49.940 --> 00:36:51.310
or in you get refinement.

00:36:51.310 --> 00:36:54.760
And I would urge you
individually to do this.

00:36:54.760 --> 00:36:58.630
It's one of the most wonderful
things that's happened to me.

00:36:58.630 --> 00:37:01.415
When something comes
along, some situation,

00:37:01.415 --> 00:37:03.290
particularly a painful
situation-- therefore,

00:37:03.290 --> 00:37:07.120
it might signal, you don't
want another one of those--

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:13.030
after you get past your
pain or at the end of it,

00:37:13.030 --> 00:37:16.990
record your pain and then
think about principles

00:37:16.990 --> 00:37:18.040
and write them down.

00:37:18.040 --> 00:37:21.280
How would you handle
that type of situation?

00:37:21.280 --> 00:37:23.470
Write it down like a diary.

00:37:23.470 --> 00:37:26.710
And when you accumulate
those and share those,

00:37:26.710 --> 00:37:28.390
that's very powerful.

00:37:33.940 --> 00:37:38.080
We have an app which we call
a Coach, which somebody says,

00:37:38.080 --> 00:37:40.310
I'm in this situation.

00:37:40.310 --> 00:37:41.540
What should I do?

00:37:41.540 --> 00:37:45.700
And then they go to that Coach,
and the relevant principles

00:37:45.700 --> 00:37:46.730
come up.

00:37:46.730 --> 00:37:48.760
But rather than
just my principles,

00:37:48.760 --> 00:37:52.330
I'm going to make it that
each successful person--

00:37:52.330 --> 00:37:55.430
I'm going to get, I
don't know, Larry Page's

00:37:55.430 --> 00:37:58.570
principles, XYZ's principles
for that situation,

00:37:58.570 --> 00:38:00.100
and you have that there.

00:38:00.100 --> 00:38:01.750
And then you have
your own principles,

00:38:01.750 --> 00:38:03.880
and you write it down
so that when you're then

00:38:03.880 --> 00:38:06.940
in a situation, you could
look at that situation

00:38:06.940 --> 00:38:10.890
and you say, what should I
do going to those principles?

00:38:10.890 --> 00:38:14.090
Because if you start to think
of that in the principled way,

00:38:14.090 --> 00:38:16.995
it's very helpful,
and they will refine.

00:38:16.995 --> 00:38:20.285
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Now,
in the five-step process,

00:38:20.285 --> 00:38:22.810
of the five steps,
what do people

00:38:22.810 --> 00:38:24.645
have the most trouble with?

00:38:24.645 --> 00:38:26.020
RAY DALIO: It's
very interesting.

00:38:26.020 --> 00:38:30.370
It really depends on
how their brains work.

00:38:30.370 --> 00:38:34.630
Like, there are some real
big picture thinkers who

00:38:34.630 --> 00:38:38.050
have no problems with goals.

00:38:38.050 --> 00:38:41.410
They know where they want to
go, but they have problems

00:38:41.410 --> 00:38:44.730
pushing through to results.

00:38:44.730 --> 00:38:49.400
So there are some people, in
terms of diagnosing things

00:38:49.400 --> 00:38:51.050
to the root cause--

00:38:51.050 --> 00:38:52.100
it's a challenge.

00:38:52.100 --> 00:38:55.790
Everybody has a problem
but one of those steps.

00:38:55.790 --> 00:38:59.870
And we see that by
observing themselves

00:38:59.870 --> 00:39:02.540
as to which step they
have a problem with,

00:39:02.540 --> 00:39:06.090
they begin to understand
how their brain works.

00:39:06.090 --> 00:39:09.830
It's not a problem, though,
if they work collectively

00:39:09.830 --> 00:39:11.450
because whatever
step they're having

00:39:11.450 --> 00:39:15.470
a problem with, another person,
if they help them with that,

00:39:15.470 --> 00:39:18.140
can really help them be
effective at that step.

