00:39:21.170 --> 00:39:22.970
The key to success
in life, really,

00:39:22.970 --> 00:39:25.820
is largely knowing
what you're not good at

00:39:25.820 --> 00:39:29.930
and who can help you
be good at those things

00:39:29.930 --> 00:39:32.454
so that you can lean on
each other and be effective.

00:39:32.454 --> 00:39:33.620
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Excellent.

00:39:33.620 --> 00:39:35.600
In the book, you mentioned
Joseph Campbell's

00:39:35.600 --> 00:39:37.070
"Hero's Journey."

00:39:37.070 --> 00:39:39.890
And what type of
impact did his work

00:39:39.890 --> 00:39:41.880
have on you with
your philosophy?

00:39:41.880 --> 00:39:47.480
RAY DALIO: Well, my son
gave it to me in 2014,

00:39:47.480 --> 00:39:49.020
way late in my journey.

00:39:49.020 --> 00:39:54.380
But I was at a particular point
in my journey where I was--

00:39:54.380 --> 00:39:59.570
he gave it to me at the late
stage, the stage are now at.

00:39:59.570 --> 00:40:02.990
He described returning the boon.

00:40:02.990 --> 00:40:11.120
And returning the moon is the
stage where you learned a lot.

00:40:11.120 --> 00:40:15.230
And some people learn a lot,
and then they go to retirement.

00:40:15.230 --> 00:40:19.120
And he was making the point
that when you learn a lot,

00:40:19.120 --> 00:40:23.010
you pass along that to others.

00:40:23.010 --> 00:40:25.670
And he described
it very vividly.

00:40:25.670 --> 00:40:30.200
Like, I don't like
public attention.

00:40:30.200 --> 00:40:33.170
I don't like all of that.

00:40:33.170 --> 00:40:37.730
But he described it
as at that stage,

00:40:37.730 --> 00:40:40.485
how important it is to pass
along what you learned,

00:40:40.485 --> 00:40:43.100
and he described it as
a difficult process.

00:40:43.100 --> 00:40:45.980
And then when you do
that so that others are

00:40:45.980 --> 00:40:50.300
successful without you,
then you get to a stage

00:40:50.300 --> 00:40:52.940
where you're free to live
and free to die because you

00:40:52.940 --> 00:40:55.010
don't have that obligation.

00:40:55.010 --> 00:40:57.050
So that's where he caught me.

00:40:57.050 --> 00:40:59.480
But if you read the book,
it's very interesting.

00:40:59.480 --> 00:41:02.960
Or in my book, I
recounted in a few pages

00:41:02.960 --> 00:41:05.660
what the "Hero's Journey" is.

00:41:05.660 --> 00:41:09.480
And you start to think about,
where am I on this path?

00:41:09.480 --> 00:41:13.160
"The Hero's Journey"-- you
probably don't know the book.

00:41:13.160 --> 00:41:14.744
"Hero of 1,000
Faces" is the book--

00:41:14.744 --> 00:41:15.410
Joseph Campbell.

00:41:15.410 --> 00:41:19.430
What he did is he went through
history and myths and so on,

00:41:19.430 --> 00:41:22.310
and he says there's a
certain type of person who

00:41:22.310 --> 00:41:26.180
has a taste for adventure
and goes through that

00:41:26.180 --> 00:41:30.020
and then has their battles, and
they have the wins and losses.

00:41:30.020 --> 00:41:34.160
And then the mission
becomes important.

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:37.100
And others become more
important than themselves.

00:41:37.100 --> 00:41:38.030
And they rise.

00:41:38.030 --> 00:41:40.470
We can call that spirituality,
whatever that is.

00:41:40.470 --> 00:41:44.360
But it is the basis
of "Star Wars."

00:41:47.240 --> 00:41:48.480
His book was.

00:41:48.480 --> 00:41:51.320
So it's that notion
of that journey.

00:41:51.320 --> 00:41:53.090
And it's a good book.

00:41:53.090 --> 00:41:56.240
In my case, I happened to read
it at that particular spot.

00:41:56.240 --> 00:41:58.160
But anybody referring
to it probably

00:41:58.160 --> 00:42:00.920
would find, oh, that's me there.

00:42:00.920 --> 00:42:04.360
One of the biggest
things was the abyss.

00:42:04.360 --> 00:42:05.480
What is your abyss?

00:42:05.480 --> 00:42:07.460
There will come a
time that you are

00:42:07.460 --> 00:42:09.770
going to have a
terrible situation,

00:42:09.770 --> 00:42:11.710
and you're going to--

00:42:11.710 --> 00:42:13.430
miserable.

00:42:13.430 --> 00:42:19.150
And how you reflect
on that situation

00:42:19.150 --> 00:42:22.380
and whether you have
a metamorphosis,

00:42:22.380 --> 00:42:24.480
a change, a personal change--

00:42:24.480 --> 00:42:29.190
me, in my case,
happened in 1982.

00:42:29.190 --> 00:42:36.100
I was publicly dead
wrong in the markets.

00:42:36.100 --> 00:42:40.530
I don't know if I'd take the
time to tell you the story.

00:42:40.530 --> 00:42:42.649
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:42.649 --> 00:42:44.190
JORDAN THIBODEAU:
You have the floor.

00:42:46.700 --> 00:42:49.100
RAY DALIO: Oh, yeah.

00:42:49.100 --> 00:42:53.040
So I formed Bridgewater in 1975.

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:55.580
And I had a small company.

00:42:55.580 --> 00:42:56.250
And I analyzed.

00:42:56.250 --> 00:43:02.220
And I had done calculations
that American banks had

00:43:02.220 --> 00:43:06.120
lent to emerging countries a lot
more money than those countries

00:43:06.120 --> 00:43:09.030
are going to be
able to pay back.

00:43:09.030 --> 00:43:12.300
And as a result, we were
going to have debt defaults

00:43:12.300 --> 00:43:15.140
and a debt crisis.

00:43:15.140 --> 00:43:17.970
And that was a very, very, very
controversial point of view.

00:43:20.520 --> 00:43:22.890
And it turned out,
in that regard,

00:43:22.890 --> 00:43:27.120
to be right Mexico
defaulted in August, 1982.

00:43:27.120 --> 00:43:31.240
And I thought we were going
to have an economic collapse.

00:43:31.240 --> 00:43:33.360
So I received a
lot of attention.

00:43:33.360 --> 00:43:34.860
I was asked to
testify to Congress

00:43:34.860 --> 00:43:36.490
to explain the situation.

00:43:36.490 --> 00:43:39.420
I went on "Wall Street Week,"
which was a show of the time.

00:43:39.420 --> 00:43:41.340
And I believed
that we were going

00:43:41.340 --> 00:43:43.590
to have this economic collapse.

00:43:43.590 --> 00:43:47.977
That was the exact bottom of
the stock market, exact bottom

00:43:47.977 --> 00:43:48.810
of the stock market.

00:43:48.810 --> 00:43:51.240
I could not have
been more wrong.

00:43:51.240 --> 00:43:54.510
Not only was I more
wrong, I lost money.

00:43:54.510 --> 00:43:55.600
I lost money for me.

00:43:55.600 --> 00:43:57.030
I lost money for my clients.

00:43:57.030 --> 00:44:01.410
I was so broke that I had
to borrow $4,000 from my dad

00:44:01.410 --> 00:44:04.170
to help to take
care of my family.

00:44:04.170 --> 00:44:08.730
It was a very, very
painful, painful mistake.

00:44:08.730 --> 00:44:11.610
But with reflection,
I would say it

00:44:11.610 --> 00:44:14.940
was one of the best things
that happened to me because it

00:44:14.940 --> 00:44:19.070
shifted my mindset from
thinking, I'm right,

00:44:19.070 --> 00:44:22.790
to asking myself, how
do I know I'm right?

00:44:22.790 --> 00:44:25.440
It gave me the
humility that I needed

00:44:25.440 --> 00:44:27.360
to balance with my audacity.

00:44:27.360 --> 00:44:28.590
It changed my approach.

00:44:28.590 --> 00:44:32.250
I had a metamorphosis.

00:44:32.250 --> 00:44:35.610
And each person is going to have
their own particular challenge

00:44:35.610 --> 00:44:36.670
that way.

00:44:36.670 --> 00:44:39.370
And so what I'm saying is
like in Joseph Campbell, that

00:44:39.370 --> 00:44:42.240
abyss-- he describes
that experience as,

00:44:42.240 --> 00:44:44.040
you're in the abyss.

00:44:44.040 --> 00:44:46.260
And then do you have
the metamorphosis?

00:44:46.260 --> 00:44:50.070
And that metamorphosis
is a humility,

00:44:50.070 --> 00:44:52.440
and I'm worried that you
might not get it right,

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:54.720
and how do you get the
best triangulation.

00:44:54.720 --> 00:44:57.090
That's motivated the
idea meritocracy,

00:44:57.090 --> 00:45:01.440
bringing the best independent
thinkers to work together.

00:45:01.440 --> 00:45:02.770
So that's what that's like.

00:45:02.770 --> 00:45:04.024
So anyway, it's a good book.

