00:47:38.530 --> 00:47:41.560
rates, from opiates from
suicides, the greatest

00:47:41.560 --> 00:47:43.700
change in incomes.

00:47:43.700 --> 00:47:46.030
It's a bad economy.

00:47:46.030 --> 00:47:49.510
And then there's this
economy on the top.

00:47:49.510 --> 00:47:51.940
And I divided it 60%.

00:47:51.940 --> 00:47:54.650
I could have
divided it 20%, 80%,

00:47:54.650 --> 00:47:57.390
and the picture would be
basically the same, not only

00:47:57.390 --> 00:48:00.870
in terms of
usefulness and so on,

00:48:00.870 --> 00:48:04.040
the death rates
rising all of this.

00:48:04.040 --> 00:48:05.810
So it's a phenomenon.

00:48:05.810 --> 00:48:09.250
And it's coming as a result
of a number of things.

00:48:09.250 --> 00:48:12.190
Technology's a big
influence on that.

00:48:12.190 --> 00:48:14.992
Globalization, in many ways,
is a big influence on that.

00:48:14.992 --> 00:48:15.950
There are other things.

00:48:15.950 --> 00:48:18.310
But anyway, that exists.

00:48:18.310 --> 00:48:27.660
If you have rich and
poor together and living

00:48:27.660 --> 00:48:30.210
next to each other in
the same community,

00:48:30.210 --> 00:48:34.920
and they share a budget where
they have to divide the pie,

00:48:34.920 --> 00:48:37.350
and you have an
economic downturn,

00:48:37.350 --> 00:48:39.270
you're going to have a conflict.

00:48:39.270 --> 00:48:41.520
You're going to have
some form of conflict.

00:48:41.520 --> 00:48:47.834
And so populism is
an extension of that.

00:48:47.834 --> 00:48:49.500
This isn't the first
time this happened.

00:48:49.500 --> 00:48:51.760
Like I say, everything's
another one of those.

00:48:51.760 --> 00:48:54.702
So in the study on populism,
which is also on LinkedIn,

00:48:54.702 --> 00:48:56.160
if you're interested
in reading it,

00:48:56.160 --> 00:48:58.770
I looked at 14
populist cases and what

00:48:58.770 --> 00:49:01.680
is a classic, iconic
populist case like,

00:49:01.680 --> 00:49:02.840
and how do they work?

00:49:02.840 --> 00:49:05.340
And so you can read about those.

00:49:05.340 --> 00:49:07.950
And there was an
iconic way of populism.

00:49:07.950 --> 00:49:12.760
So that dynamic of that
disparity, that problem,

00:49:12.760 --> 00:49:14.910
which I think will be
particularly important

00:49:14.910 --> 00:49:18.000
when we have the next economic
downturn, which I think,

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:19.874
probably--

00:49:19.874 --> 00:49:22.290
I'm almost certain it will be
before the next presidential

00:49:22.290 --> 00:49:24.720
election, which
means that I think

00:49:24.720 --> 00:49:29.200
there'll be a lot of polarity,
and I think it's a big issue.

00:49:29.200 --> 00:49:31.690
So that's the issue.

00:49:31.690 --> 00:49:35.760
It's both an issue
of equity, and it's

00:49:35.760 --> 00:49:39.630
an issue of practicality that
we have to deal with that.

00:49:39.630 --> 00:49:43.950
I would say it should be a
national initiative, I would

00:49:43.950 --> 00:49:48.510
say, led by the president
or somebody in which you

00:49:48.510 --> 00:49:49.650
take the metrics.

00:49:49.650 --> 00:49:52.500
I give metrics for that
boy part of the population.

00:49:52.500 --> 00:49:54.240
You could look at the metrics.

00:49:54.240 --> 00:49:57.570
And if you have metrics,
is it improving?

00:49:57.570 --> 00:49:59.490
Or is it worsening?

00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:01.120
And what does it look like?

00:50:01.120 --> 00:50:03.810
And then you have initiatives of
how to be able to deal with it.

00:50:03.810 --> 00:50:09.880
I think that
economically, there are

00:50:09.880 --> 00:50:13.630
many things that can be done.

00:50:13.630 --> 00:50:14.890
I live in Connecticut.

00:50:14.890 --> 00:50:20.450
Connecticut has the highest per
capita income in the country.

00:50:20.450 --> 00:50:26.410
But it consists of rich people
next to a lot of poor people,

00:50:26.410 --> 00:50:29.494
and the averages
exist, and she works

00:50:29.494 --> 00:50:30.910
in the school
system with what are

00:50:30.910 --> 00:50:34.975
called disengaged and
disconnected youth.

00:50:34.975 --> 00:50:39.790
A disengaged student is
one who goes to school

00:50:39.790 --> 00:50:42.420
but really doesn't study for
tests, doesn't take the tests,

00:50:42.420 --> 00:50:44.920
fails, is basically
a failing student.

00:50:44.920 --> 00:50:48.210
And a disconnected is one
that doesn't go to school.

00:50:48.210 --> 00:50:49.710
They don't even
know where they are.

00:50:49.710 --> 00:50:51.250
They don't come to school.

00:50:51.250 --> 00:50:54.640
22% of the students
in Connecticut

00:50:54.640 --> 00:50:58.150
are either disengaged
or disconnected.

00:50:58.150 --> 00:51:01.930
And you look at the
reasons for that.

00:51:01.930 --> 00:51:06.050
And you look at the
cost of what that means.

00:51:06.050 --> 00:51:07.720
There are programs--

00:51:07.720 --> 00:51:09.100
I won't get into this a lot.

00:51:09.100 --> 00:51:13.510
But there are programs that
help to keep the kids in schools

00:51:13.510 --> 00:51:17.080
and get them engaged that
are needlessly not in there.

00:51:17.080 --> 00:51:19.630
And yet if they graduate
from high school,

00:51:19.630 --> 00:51:22.330
the incarceration rates change.

00:51:22.330 --> 00:51:24.160
The crime rates change.

00:51:24.160 --> 00:51:29.800
Average cost of incarceration is
between 85 and $125,000 a year.

00:51:29.800 --> 00:51:34.010
So you think of the cost of the
society that is having that.

00:51:34.010 --> 00:51:36.550
Anyway, there are
those kinds of issues

00:51:36.550 --> 00:51:39.760
that I think have to be looked
at, essentially, forthrightly.

00:51:39.760 --> 00:51:41.260
That's got to be
viewed as an issue.

00:51:41.260 --> 00:51:42.343
There's got to be metrics.

00:51:42.343 --> 00:51:45.735
And there's got to be processes
in place for dealing with it.

00:51:45.735 --> 00:51:47.480
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Yeah.

