depending on the nature
of the decision rule--

01:18:14.180 --> 01:18:17.360
I can test how it would
have worked in the past

01:18:17.360 --> 01:18:21.550
and get some sense of it.

01:18:21.550 --> 01:18:27.260
Like in my investment
decision rules,

01:18:27.260 --> 01:18:30.170
I say they have to be
timeless and universal.

01:18:30.170 --> 01:18:34.490
So that means I test them
from 1900 to the present.

01:18:34.490 --> 01:18:36.500
I test them in all
different countries.

01:18:36.500 --> 01:18:39.320
And being able to
specify them then

01:18:39.320 --> 01:18:42.560
allows me to get a
sense of distribution

01:18:42.560 --> 01:18:44.840
of those types of probabilities.

01:18:44.840 --> 01:18:47.490
Some things are qualitative
and it's different.

01:18:47.490 --> 01:18:50.390
But I think that
being aware of what

01:18:50.390 --> 01:18:52.670
I was describing
in the book of how

01:18:52.670 --> 01:18:58.370
to think about that
probability helps you.

01:18:58.370 --> 01:19:01.430
Some things-- it's just
the mind has got to do

01:19:01.430 --> 01:19:04.820
and by triangulating
with others.

01:19:04.820 --> 01:19:08.360
I think in my business
I tend to think

01:19:08.360 --> 01:19:10.400
about that probability
of decision-making

01:19:10.400 --> 01:19:12.470
because I also have
one of the benefits

01:19:12.470 --> 01:19:15.590
that I get very clear paybacks.

01:19:15.590 --> 01:19:18.170
I get graded every
day, essentially,

01:19:18.170 --> 01:19:19.200
by the performance.

01:19:19.200 --> 01:19:21.790
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Right.

01:19:21.790 --> 01:19:22.870
AUDIENCE: Hi.

01:19:22.870 --> 01:19:25.420
So having read the
book I definitely

01:19:25.420 --> 01:19:30.490
agree with you that having
principles is a good thing.

01:19:30.490 --> 01:19:32.440
And they help you
spot another one

01:19:32.440 --> 01:19:34.810
of those kind of situations.

01:19:34.810 --> 01:19:39.256
But one thing that I didn't
quite see covered in the book,

01:19:39.256 --> 01:19:40.630
and I'm curious
to hear about, is

01:19:40.630 --> 01:19:42.790
at what point do you
decide that you've

01:19:42.790 --> 01:19:46.840
seen enough of these situations
that they need a principle.

01:19:46.840 --> 01:19:50.169
Because you could have a
principle for every event

01:19:50.169 --> 01:19:50.710
that you see.

01:19:50.710 --> 01:19:52.995
But then you might
be overfitting there.

01:19:52.995 --> 01:19:54.370
On the other hand,
you could wait

01:19:54.370 --> 01:19:57.790
for too many of
these, at which point

01:19:57.790 --> 01:20:00.040
you're probably
overgeneralizing, so--

01:20:00.040 --> 01:20:00.340
RAY DALIO: I think what--

01:20:00.340 --> 01:20:01.840
AUDIENCE: What's
the meta principle?

01:20:01.840 --> 01:20:05.260
RAY DALIO: My experience is
it's just like a big thing comes

01:20:05.260 --> 01:20:09.790
along, and do you start there?

01:20:09.790 --> 01:20:10.330
OK.

01:20:10.330 --> 01:20:12.359
Now do you have that?

01:20:12.359 --> 01:20:13.650
AUDIENCE: So it's the size of--

01:20:13.650 --> 01:20:15.316
RAY DALIO: And then
what-- you know, OK.

01:20:15.316 --> 01:20:17.130
Now, you're doing it.

01:20:17.130 --> 01:20:19.880
And now another big
thing comes along,

01:20:19.880 --> 01:20:22.080
and you have one for that.

01:20:22.080 --> 01:20:27.000
And if you do that then
you'll find out whether you're

01:20:27.000 --> 01:20:29.250
getting to too small stuff.

01:20:29.250 --> 01:20:31.287
But you probably
won't have a problem

01:20:31.287 --> 01:20:33.120
with the too small stuff
because you will be

01:20:33.120 --> 01:20:35.100
struggling with the big stuff.

01:20:35.100 --> 01:20:40.110
So I have-- I don't
know how many principals

01:20:40.110 --> 01:20:42.840
are in the book, actually--
but anyway, a few hundred.

01:20:42.840 --> 01:20:47.290
And the reason was
because I needed each one.

01:20:47.290 --> 01:20:51.330
What you find is when you
encounter something again,

01:20:51.330 --> 01:20:53.460
then you start to--
is it a subprinciple?

01:20:53.460 --> 01:20:54.460
Is it another principle?

01:20:54.460 --> 01:20:55.800
And you get them organized.

01:20:55.800 --> 01:21:03.630
But the way I did it was I
wrote them first on paper.

01:21:03.630 --> 01:21:06.420
But then I started dropping
them in the BlackBerry

01:21:06.420 --> 01:21:07.720
when I was thinking.

01:21:07.720 --> 01:21:09.490
And I would take that--
bits and pieces--

01:21:09.490 --> 01:21:10.909
and I would collect them--

01:21:10.909 --> 01:21:11.700
just your thoughts.

01:21:11.700 --> 01:21:13.740
So just start collecting them.

01:21:13.740 --> 01:21:15.690
Make sure you do it
with the big ones.

01:21:15.690 --> 01:21:18.040
And, yeah, you don't have
to do it with everything.

01:21:18.040 --> 01:21:19.958
AUDIENCE: So the size of event.

01:21:19.958 --> 01:21:22.619
Thank you.

01:21:22.619 --> 01:21:25.160
AUDIENCE: I think the process
of decision-making and conflict

01:21:25.160 --> 01:21:27.576
resolution that you're talking
about makes a lot of sense.

01:21:27.576 --> 01:21:30.230
But I'm wondering if
a precondition for it

01:21:30.230 --> 01:21:35.280
is that the group agrees
on the general goal,

01:21:35.280 --> 01:21:36.600
even if not how to do it.

01:21:36.600 --> 01:21:40.040
And so that works well in
Bridgewater, here at Google.

01:21:40.040 --> 01:21:42.772
But in the public policy
arena I'm not sure

01:21:42.772 --> 01:21:45.230
how that works, because people
represent different interest

01:21:45.230 --> 01:21:47.900
groups, and they fundamentally
have a different objective.

01:21:47.900 --> 01:21:51.410
Do you see any modifications
as required for that case?

01:21:51.410 --> 01:21:53.270
RAY DALIO: I think
in all relationships

01:21:53.270 --> 01:21:55.880
the beginning is
defining how you're

01:21:55.880 --> 01:21:58.670
going to be with each other--

01:21:58.670 --> 01:22:01.220
clear rules.

01:22:01.220 --> 01:22:05.860
So Bridgewater's rules are
different than Google's rules,

01:22:05.860 --> 01:22:08.210
which are different from
the government's rules.

01:22:08.210 --> 01:22:11.320
Then within any
organization, there

01:22:11.320 --> 01:22:13.330
are subgroups that
can decide how

01:22:13.330 --> 01:22:15.640
are we going to behave with
each other in a way that

01:22:15.640 --> 01:22:17.800
doesn't conflict with that.

01:22:17.800 --> 01:22:22.330
So I would suspect that if I was
president of the United States

01:22:22.330 --> 01:22:25.060
I would have an ideal
meritocratic way that

01:22:25.060 --> 01:22:26.800
might be different
than Donald Trump has,

01:22:26.800 --> 01:22:29.200
who might be different
than somebody else has.

01:22:29.200 --> 01:22:32.930
So you, within your
group, can decide, OK,

01:22:32.930 --> 01:22:36.250
do we want to be idea do we
[INAUDIBLE] meritocratic?

01:22:36.250 --> 01:22:38.320
Can we talk about these
things in this way?

01:22:38.320 --> 01:22:43.470
Do we want to be transparent and
make those types of decisions.

01:22:43.470 --> 01:22:46.702
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:22:46.702 --> 01:22:48.580
AUDIENCE: Mr. Dalio,
thanks for sharing.

01:22:48.580 --> 01:22:51.830
My question pertains to the
dot system that you mention.

01:22:51.830 --> 01:22:54.670
So you seem to have calculated
the believable score

01:22:54.670 --> 01:22:57.670
for a person over time,
collecting information

01:22:57.670 --> 01:23:00.160
to help you with
decision-making process.

01:23:00.160 --> 01:23:03.040
Has there been your dot
system been proven wrong

01:23:03.040 --> 01:23:05.320
where you calculate, say,
someone's believable score

01:23:05.320 --> 01:23:08.140
to be very low, when
over time has been shown,

01:23:08.140 --> 01:23:12.250
actually, this person is
very believable in his--

01:23:12.250 --> 01:23:13.210
has that been shown?

01:23:13.210 --> 01:23:15.130
RAY DALIO: Well,
I think the way--

01:23:15.130 --> 01:23:17.470
I think of it more like
the way that you're

01:23:17.470 --> 01:23:19.340
sort of semi-describing it.

01:23:19.340 --> 01:23:23.980
If over time it's
shown to be wrong--

01:23:23.980 --> 01:23:28.270
quote, "wrong,"-- that
must mean that you've

01:23:28.270 --> 01:23:31.390
evolved to the point
where you believe

01:23:31.390 --> 01:23:35.270
that that verdict is reliable.

01:23:35.270 --> 01:23:39.550
So the evolutionary system must
have taken you to that spot.

01:23:39.550 --> 01:23:45.400
The way I look at it is with
sample size and with a lot

01:23:45.400 --> 01:23:49.510
of consensus, or processes
of coming up with those

01:23:49.510 --> 01:23:52.570
algorithms, you have an
evolutionary process--

01:23:52.570 --> 01:23:54.970
more data, more process--

01:23:54.970 --> 01:23:57.820
to get at the definition
of what is true.

01:23:57.820 --> 01:23:59.800
And then it's that
mechanism that's

01:23:59.800 --> 01:24:02.320
always constantly
evaluating, so that there

01:24:02.320 --> 01:24:05.350
are statistical
ways of measuring

01:24:05.350 --> 01:24:08.110
for a group as a whole
how accurate it is.

01:24:08.110 --> 01:24:10.750
You might have something that
might be something as simple

01:24:10.750 --> 01:24:12.710
as, I would have a test.

01:24:12.710 --> 01:24:15.190
Like, I can test
how you know math.

01:24:15.190 --> 01:24:17.020
And that could be an
objective measure.

01:24:17.020 --> 01:24:20.500
In some areas you can't
have that objectivity.

01:24:20.500 --> 01:24:23.080
On some notion of
creativity much [INAUDIBLE]

01:24:23.080 --> 01:24:25.070
you'll have different measures.

01:24:25.070 --> 01:24:30.040
So the point that I'm saying
is that you're constantly

01:24:30.040 --> 01:24:32.020
never good enough.

01:24:32.020 --> 01:24:35.870
And you're constantly
evolving toward better.

01:24:35.870 --> 01:24:38.800
And that is the best way--

01:24:38.800 --> 01:24:41.200
by comparison to other ways--

01:24:41.200 --> 01:24:43.382
which don't do that.

01:24:43.382 --> 01:24:45.215
AUDIENCE: And is there
a plan to open source

01:24:45.215 --> 01:24:48.690
this so that the system
can be shared and used

01:24:48.690 --> 01:24:49.715
