01:32:04.770 --> 01:32:09.750
to, within an asset class, the
individual securities chosen,

01:32:09.750 --> 01:32:13.230
as distinct from the
differences when he says

01:32:13.230 --> 01:32:15.990
capital allocation,
he's referring

01:32:15.990 --> 01:32:19.530
to the different types
of asset classes.

01:32:19.530 --> 01:32:22.290
I presume that that's what
he's referring to in that way,

01:32:22.290 --> 01:32:23.740
and that's correct.

01:32:23.740 --> 01:32:25.380
In other words,
the average stock

01:32:25.380 --> 01:32:29.580
is 60% correlated with
the average other stock,

01:32:29.580 --> 01:32:31.960
so there's a high
correlation of stocks.

01:32:31.960 --> 01:32:34.150
They will go up
and down together.

01:32:34.150 --> 01:32:37.910
And because of that,
you're going to--

01:32:37.910 --> 01:32:43.009
it almost, past a certain point,
doesn't matter how many stocks.

01:32:43.009 --> 01:32:44.550
I cover that, by
the way, in the book

01:32:44.550 --> 01:32:46.540
in terms of the
math of literally

01:32:46.540 --> 01:32:50.500
